Optional improvements (only if you want extra safety)

1. Preserve permissions & symlinks explicitly

Your tar command is already good, but Iâ€™d slightly tweak it for long-term restores:

tar -cvpzf /sdcard/Download/termux_backup.tar.gz $HOME

-p preserves permissions (useful if you restore into Linux later)

Explicit $HOME avoids edge cases if ~ expands weirdly



---

2. Split huge backups (Drive-friendly)

If your Termux home is several GB, Drive uploads can silently fail. Safer option:

tar -cvpzf - $HOME | split -b 2G - /sdcard/Download/termux_backup.tar.gz.part_

Later you can reassemble with:

cat termux_backup.tar.gz.part_* > termux_backup.tar.gz


---

3. Extra paranoia for SQLite

If Prompt Genie matters a lot, do both:

sqlite3 your_database.db "PRAGMA integrity_check;"
sqlite3 your_database.db .dump > /sdcard/Download/prompt_genie_export.sql

If integrity check returns ok, you know the dump is trustworthy.


---

4. Git repos without remotes

If you have repos that arenâ€™t pushed anywhere and you want them future-proof:

git bundle create project.bundle --all

A .bundle file is a full portable repo snapshot â€” perfect for Drive.


